<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-04-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-04-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="126" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d126">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">810.154/917</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">O’Donoghue</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 962</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-04-27">April 27, 1936</date>.<lb/>[Received May
                                1.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Supplementing the Legation’s despatch No.
                            947, of April 15, 1936,<note n="14" xml:id="d126fn14">Not
                                printed.</note> in connection with the acceptance by Guatemala of
                            the route laid down in the reconnaissance survey for the Inter-American
                            Highway, I have the honor to transmit herewith a copy and translation of
                            a Foreign Office note dated April 24, 1936,<note n="14" xml:id="d126fn15">Not printed.</note> stating that the Government
                            perceives no objection to accepting the route in question “reserving the
                            right to give the necessary notice upon making any later change”.</p>
                        <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Sidney E.
                            O’Donoghue</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>